{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 17:07:13.868152", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report — SDN spine–leaf lab\\nDate: (current capture)\\n\\nSummary\\n- Observed a clear data-plane failure: hosts in the 10.0.0.0/24 subnets cannot reach one another (L2/L3 within the fabric fails).\\n- The forwarding elements (OVS datapath/bridge) on all switches appear to be non-operational (ovs-system / bridge interfaces in DOWN state), while physical interfaces are UP. This prevents ARP resolution and host-to-host traffic.\\n- Controller is configured on each OVS bridge (tcp:20.0.0.100:6633) but the switches’ datapath/bridge state suggests they cannot forward host traffic even if controller connectivity existed.\\n\\nAffected components (localized)\\n- leaf_1 (OVS datapath / bridge)\\n- leaf_2 (OVS datapath / bridge)\\n- spine_1 (OVS datapath / bridge)\\n- All hosts attached to leaf bridges (host_1_1, host_1_2, host_2_1, host_2_2, etc.) are impacted indirectly: they cannot ARP/communicate off their NICs because the attached switch datapaths are not forwarding.\\n\\nKey evidence (collected commands & outputs)\\n1) Host-to-host ping (example)\\n- From host_1_1 -> host_1_2:\\n  - ping result: \"Destination Host Unreachable\" (4/4 lost).\\n  - This indicates the local system could not deliver/resolve the neighbor (ARP failure or missing L2 path).\\n\\n2) Neighbor table on hosts\\n- host_1_1: \"10.0.0.2 dev eth0 FAILED\"\\n- host_1_2: has FAILED entries for peers (10.0.0.1, 10.0.0.3)\\n- Interpretation: ARP resolution is failing (neighbor entries marked FAILED), consistent with switches not forwarding ARP.\\n\\n3) Host network config (representative)\\n- host_1_1: eth0 10.0.0.1/24 (no default route to 20.0.0.0/24 — normal for hosts on access subnet).\\n- host_1_1 ping to controller 20.0.0.100 -> \"Network is unreachable\" (hosts have no route to management network; hosts rely on local L2 to reach other hosts).\\n\\n4) OVS/bridge state on switches\\n- ovs-vsctl show (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1) shows each Bridge configured and Controller set to \"tcp:20.0.0.100:6633\".\\n- BUT ip addr / ifconfig of switch hosts shows:\\n  - ovs-system (the OVS datapath interface): state DOWN\\n  - bridge name (leaf_1 / leaf_2 / spine_1) also shown as state DOWN\\n  - The physical interfaces (eth0..ethN) are UP and are slaves to ovs-system, but the ovs-system device itself is DOWN.\\n  - Example (spine_1): eth0..eth3 are UP and enslaved to ovs-system, but ovs-system and the bridge interface are DOWN. spine_1 has management IP on a separate eth (eth4) and that management interface is UP (20.0.0.1).\\n\\n5) ovs-appctl invocation\\n- Attempted ovs-appctl -t ovs-vswitchd connection-status returned \"command not valid\" on these images (no additional controller-state info available). This prevents confirming controller session state from that tool, but the ovs-system/bridge DOWN state is sufficient to explain the data-plane failure.\\n\\nProbable root cause (analysis)\\n- The root cause is at the switch datapath/bridge layer: the OVS datapath device (ovs-system) is DOWN on the three OVS switches (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1). Because the datapath/bridge is not operational, L2 traffic (including ARP) is not being forwarded between host ports attached to the bridges. This manifests as FAILED neighbor entries on hosts and \"Destination Host Unreachable\" when pinging same-subnet hosts.\\n- Possible underlying causes (diagnostic hypotheses, not remediations): the ovs kernel datapath is not loaded/initialized or the userspace OVS daemon (ovs-vswitchd/ovsdb-server) failed to attach/configure the kernel datapath, or an internal OVS datapath device was administratively down. The management interfaces (20.0.0.x) on switches are up, so management-plane reachability for the switches themselves may be present even though the datapath is down.\\n\\nImpact\\n- All intra-subnet host-to-host traffic fails (observed).\\n- Any services relying on L2 connectivity through these OVS bridges are unavailable.\\n- The SDN controller may be configured on the bridges but even a connected controller could not restore host connectivity while the datapath is down.\\n\\nSupporting excerpts (concise)\\n- host_1_1 ping host_1_2: 4 sent, 0 received, \"Destination Host Unreachable\".\\n- host_1_1 ip neigh: \"10.0.0.2 dev eth0 FAILED\".\\n- leaf_1 ovs-vsctl show: Bridge leaf_1, Controller \"tcp:20.0.0.100:6633\".\\n- leaf_1 ip output: ovs-system: state DOWN; leaf_1 bridge: state DOWN; eth0..eth6: UP (enslaved).\\n- leaf_2 and spine_1 show the same pattern (datapath/bridge DOWN, phys interfaces UP).\\n- spine_1 management interface: inet 20.0.0.1/24 (management net present).\\n\\nConclusion\\n- There is a clear anomaly: OVS datapath/bridge layer is not operational on the switches, causing complete failure of host-level connectivity in the data plane. The problem localizes to the OVS datapath/bridge on leaf_1, leaf_2 and spine_1. The most likely root cause is an OVS datapath initialization/service failure (kernel datapath not attached or userspace OVS components not making the datapath operative).\\n\\nIf you want, I can collect additional targeted evidence to further narrow the root cause (examples: service status of ovs-vswitchd/ovsdb-server, relevant logs (ovs-vswitchd/ovsdb-server), dmesg for kernel datapath errors, or controller connectivity from the switch management interface). I will not perform any remediation steps unless you request them., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='38137822-7c04-463b-9f89-f2223427bd27'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
